This command will find 2 consecutive lines starting with `constant` and replace the 2nd one with `X`:

    sed &#39;/^constant.*$/ { N; s/\(^constant.*\n\)constant.*$/\1X/; }&#39;

**UPDATE**

Based on the additional information you&#39;ve provided, this should do the trick:

    sed &#39;/^after .*$/ { N; s/^after .*\(\nafter .*\)$/(no information)\1/; }&#39;

**UPDATE #2**

Another solution provided by @potong in the comments:

    sed -E &#39;/^after/{N;s/.*(\nafter)/(no information)\1/;P;D}&#39;

This will also work in cases where there are more than 2 &quot;problematic&quot; lines in a row and will replace all of them with `(no information)`.

It doesn&#39;t read a class-level `/** @test */` annotation, but a default phpunit.xml file does also has the testsuite defined with a filename suffix:

     &lt;testsuites&gt;
         &lt;testsuite name=&quot;default&quot;&gt;
             &lt;directory suffix=&quot;Test.php&quot;&gt;tests&lt;/directory&gt;
         &lt;/testsuite&gt;
     &lt;/testsuites&gt;

If you run phpunit on the specific file: `vendor/bin/phpunit tests/RepoPost.php` it does run the tests, even if the filename does not match the suffix.

 You can use suffix:
   
     &lt;testsuite name=&quot;Feature&quot;&gt;
            &lt;directory suffix=&quot;Test.php&quot;&gt;./tests/Feature&lt;/directory&gt;
        &lt;/testsuite&gt;
    

Then you should rename your file to be `RepoPostTest.php`

In your phpunit.xml add the suffix attribute to the &lt;directory&gt; tags. The example will run all `.php` files, which may become risky if you have any none TestCase classes/files in there which is why its convention to suffix the classes with `Test`.

    &lt;testsuite name=&quot;Feature&quot;&gt;
        &lt;directory suffix=&quot;.php&quot;&gt;./tests/Feature&lt;/directory&gt;
    &lt;/testsuite&gt;

Hope this helps!

